Here’s exactly where the extension is deployed and what components exist right now in your Gardener landscape.

Seed/Garden side (management + seed cluster)
A) Gardener registration objects (in the Garden cluster)
These are the “plug-in” objects that tell Gardener about the extension and how to install it:

ControllerRegistration/gardener-extension-f5
ControllerDeployment/gardener-extension-f5
ControllerInstallation is OnDemand, so Gardener auto-creates one when a Shoot needs it (yours is currently gardener-extension-f5-zn8sj)
You can see them with:

kubectl --context kind-gardener-local get controllerregistration gardener-extension-f5
kubectl --context kind-gardener-local get controllerdeployment gardener-extension-f5
kubectl --context kind-gardener-local get controllerinstallations -A | grep gardener-extension-f5

B) Where the controller Pod actually runs (Seed cluster)
Gardener installs the extension controller into a generated namespace:

Namespace: extension-gardener-extension-f5-zn8sj
Workload: Deployment/gardener-extension-f5
Pod: gardener-extension-f5-... (running)
Check:

kubectl --context kind-gardener-local -n extension-gardener-extension-f5-zn8sj get deploy,pod -o wide

Per-shoot objects (Seed cluster, shoot technical namespace)
For your Shoot garden-local/local, the technical namespace is:

shoot--local--local
Inside that namespace Gardener created the Extension trigger and our controller created the per-shoot config CR:

Extension/f5-loadbalancer (type f5-loadbalancer) ← this triggers reconciliation
F5LoadBalancerConfig/f5-loadbalancer ← this is the per-shoot input
Check:

kubectl --context kind-gardener-local -n shoot--local--local get extension
kubectl --context kind-gardener-local -n shoot--local--local get f5loadbalancerconfig

