Gardener Extension F5 - Implementation Summary (LB + VIP + Virtual Server)

Overview
- This repository implements a Gardener extension that (a) reconciles a per-Shoot
	config object and (b) can call CMP/F5 APIs to provision control-plane LB pieces,
	and (c) deploys F5 CIS into Shoots once the control-plane LB is considered ready.

What was built (already in this repo)

1) Core API types (CRD)
- API group: f5.extensions.gardener.cloud
- Kind: F5LoadBalancerConfig
- Location:
	- pkg/apis/f5/v1alpha1/types.go
	- config/crd/f5loadbalancerconfigs.f5.extensions.gardener.cloud.yaml

2) Lifecycle controller (seed-side reconciliation)
- Location: pkg/controller/lifecycle/
- Responsibilities (high-level):
	- Watches per-Shoot Extension + F5LoadBalancerConfig in the Shoot technical namespace.
	- Validates control-plane VIP input readiness.
	- (Optionally) calls CMP/F5 APIs to ensure the control-plane VIP/VS.
	- Writes status back to F5LoadBalancerConfig.
	- Deploys CIS to the Shoot only when control-plane LB is ready.

3) CMP/F5 HTTP client
- Location: pkg/f5/client.go
- Supports Ce-Auth (HMAC) + organisation-name + project-id.

4) Helm chart + Gardener registration objects
- Helm chart: charts/gardener-extension-f5/
- Garden install manifests: deploy/garden/
	- controllerregistration-f5.yaml
	- controllerdeployment-f5.yaml
	- controllerinstallation-f5.yaml

5) Developer tools in this repo (to run CMP APIs)
- scripts/cmp-curl.sh
	- Curl wrapper that injects required headers and can run arbitrary endpoints via: raw METHOD PATH
- scripts/cmp-ceauth.py
	- Generates short-lived Ce-Auth tokens using API key id + secret (HMAC-SHA256)
- cmd/cmpctl
	- Small Go CLI for calling CMP endpoints with Ce-Auth.
	- Extended subcommands for LB workflows:
		- lbsvc-list, lbsvc-create, lbsvc-get
		- lbsvc-vip
		- vs-list, vs-create

Contract / data flow (Gardener)
1) Shoot is created
2) Gardener creates Extension objects in the Shoot technical namespace (seed)
3) The extension controller reconciles and ensures/configures:
	 - Control-plane VIP/VS (either via CMP API calls or “out-of-band ready” flag)
4) Once control-plane LB is ready, extension deploys CIS to the Shoot
5) CIS programs application-plane VIP/VS based on Ingress/Service objects

Where the 3 CMP calls fit (LB → VIP → Virtual Server)
This is the “same style as the TCPWave DNS integration”, but for LB objects.

A) Create LB (LBService)

	POST /api/v1/load-balancers/lb_service/
	Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

- Required headers:
	Ce-Auth: <token>
	organisation-name: qa-tenant
	project-id: 3
	ce-region: dev
	external-project: qa-first-cell
	project-name: qa-first-cell

B) Create VIP for the LB
- In many CMP deployments VIPs are created automatically as part of LBService creation.
- The UI “VIPs” tab usually calls a read endpoint like:
	GET /api/v1/load-balancers/lb_service/{lbsvc_id}/vip
- If your CMP has an explicit “create VIP” API, capture the UI Network request URL and
	we can mirror it in cmpctl/cmp-curl.

C) Create Virtual Server for that LB
- Swagger you shared earlier indicated VS endpoints shaped like:
	POST /api/v1/load-balancers/{lb_id}/virtual-servers
	GET  /api/v1/load-balancers/{lb_id}/virtual-servers
- In your environment, the LB list objects use a UUID id (e.g. gardener-lb id
	599255c2-5964-4e05-b58e-8f07cc5ece14). For VS, the exact “lb_id” to use must be
	taken from the UI Network request (some systems use lbsvc_id, some use a separate id).

